Population growth and service pressures in England

April 11, 2018

These projections can be broken down by age band, to show the trajectories for children (ages 0 to 17), younger adults (ages 18 to 65) and older adults (ages 65 and over):


From the figure above, we can see that older adults (65+) are the fastest growing age group for all types of councils, followed by children (age 0-17). Younger adults (ages 18-64) are projected to grow relatively slowly. London stands out for the fact that it has the fastest population growth in all age categories, but particularly for younger adults and children.

This shows average spending on the various age bands. We exclude spending on schools and public health.

We create a single estimate of ‘population pressure’ by weighing population growth in each age band by its corresponding share of expenditure (for each individual council).

Finally, we can illustrate how population pressure varies by geographic region. As can be seen, population pressures are greatest in the South, East and East Midlands.

df_plot5 <- df_pop1 %>% 
            filter(year == 2025,
                   age_band == 'all',
                   admin != 'County') %>% 
            left_join(select(df_info, code_mhclg, region), by= 'code_mhclg')
            
plot5 <- ggplot(data = df_plot5,
                aes(x = region, y = change_unweighted - 1)) +
          geom_jitter(size = 3, alpha = .5) +
          theme_minimal() +
          scale_y_continuous(labels=percent) +
          geom_hline(yintercept = 0, size = 0.25) +
          scale_color_manual(values = 'blue') +
          labs(
              y = "Cumulative change",
              title = paste("Population growth by region")
              )
      
plot5

A dot-density map of Dallas

 May 5, 2018
As a new arrival in Dallas, it’s taken me a while to get to grips with its layout. Its sheer size and sprawl make it difficult to identify where Dallas ends and neighboring cities begin. Expanses of new developments and construction appear to have blurred the lines between what were once distinct towns and cities. With this in mind, this post has two aims: first, to better understand the geography of Dallas, and second, to do so while exploring some of the GIS tools available in R, the open-source programming language.

Funding cuts and deprivation in England

 Apr 4, 2018
The most deprived parts of England have borne the brunt of public spending cuts since 2010. As spending now begins to increase, this could bring relief to some of the hardest-hit local councils. However, this analysis shows that the gains - unlike the cuts - will be shared fairly evenly among both affluent and deprived parts of England. In 2010 the UK government embarked on a series of major spending cuts to reduce its budget deficit, in response to the financial crisis.

la_info.xlsx Link: NA Description: Information on all local authorities, including their functions and codes. Used to map local authority (LA) codes between the various data sources. - code_mhclg: MHCLG’s typical LA codes - code_est: Codes used in the population_estimates.xlsx file - code_proj: Codes used in the population_projections.xlsx file - functions: upper-tier services (U), lower-tier (L) and fire (F) - admin: County, unitary, metropolitan district (MD), Inner London Borough (ILB), Outer London (OLB), shire district (SD)
